Final Project - Near-Earth Asteroids

Braxton Wilson, Richard Sauve

12/13/2021

Introduction

  • Keeping track of NEOs (near-earth objects) is important for the safety of our satellites, astronauts, and (in the case of large objects) the planet!
  • Another good reason to keep track of NEOs is for the potential, in the future, to be able to mine these asteroids for minerals and water.
  • Will be exploring and presenting an NEA (near-earth asteroid) dataset from Kaggle which was compiled from NASAs CNEOS website.
  • Explore the data by comparing hazardous to non-hazardous NEAs and comparing different classes of NEAs.
  • This analysis will help shed light on the following:
    • What are the differences between Hazardous and Non-Hazardous NEAs?
    • What are the differences between the classifications of NEAs?

Data Prep

  • Data set downloaded from Kaggle:

    • https://www.kaggle.com/shrutimehta/nasa-asteroids-classification

  • Data itself is from NASA

    • http://neo.jpl.nasa.gov/

  • This data is public domain and was scraped from NASAs website by Shruti Mehta in 2017. She says her inspiration for collecting this data was finding potential hazardous and non-hazardous asteroids and understanding what distinguishes the two categories.

  • From the NASA CNEOS websites about page:

    The Center for Near-Earth Object Studies (CNEOS) computes high precision orbits for Near-Earth Objects (NEOs), predicts their future motions, assesses their impact hazard, and makes these result available on this website.

  • No missing data for any of the variables!

  • Import is simple, read.csv.

  • A glimpse at the dataframe:

Variables of Interest:

Variables Description
Neo.Reference.ID ID number assigned to the asteroid by NASA
Absolute.Magnitude How visible the asteroid would be from a standardized distance away (1 AU) without any kind of obfuscation
Max.Est.Dia.KM The maximum estimation of the NEAs diameter
Min.Est.Dia.KM The minimum estimation of the NEAs diameter
Relative.Velocity.km.per.sec The velocity of the NEA relative to our vantage point
Miss.Dist.AU Distance the object missed Earth in astronomical units
Orbit.Uncertainty 0-9 logarithmic scale of the uncertainty of an objects orbit
Eccentricity Measure of an objects deviation from a circular orbit, 0 = Perfect circle, 0 < and < 1 is an ellipse, 1 is parabolic, and > 1 is hyperbolic
Semi.Major.Axis Half of the major axis of the elliptical orbit
Perihelion.Dist The point in an objects orbit closest to the sun
Aphelion.Dist The point in an objects orbit furthest from the sun
Hazardous Whether or not the asteroid meets the requirements to be deemed potentially hazardous

Exploratory Data Analysis

  • When looking through the observations available for NEAs in this data set, I wondered what made an asteroid hazardous or not.

  • This was easily answered via NASAs CNEOS website:

    Potentially Hazardous Asteroids (PHAs) are currently defined based on parameters that measure the asteroids potential to make threatening close approaches to the Earth. Specifically, all asteroids with an Earth Minimum Orbit Intersection Distance (MOID) of 0.05 au or less and an absolute magnitude (H) of 22.0 or less are considered PHAs. In other words, asteroids that cant get any closer to the Earth (i.e., MOID) than 0.05 au (roughly 7,480,000 km or 4,650,000 mi) or are smaller than about 140 m (~500 ft) in diameter (i.e., H = 22.0 with assumed albedo of 14%) are not considered PHAs.

  • On that same page, a graphic explaining how to calculate NEA classifications was available.

Orbital Uncertainty

  • A look at the differences between Hazardous/Non-Hazardous NEAs and NEA classes of Orbital Uncertainty.

  • Hazardous NEAs have significantly less orbital uncertainty on average than non-hazardous NEAs excluding Atiras class NEAs.
  • Part of the Orbital Uncertainty parameters calculation is the number of observations, so it very well may be the case that astronomers spend more time observing potentially hazardous asteroids.
  • There is very little orbital uncertainty in Atiras class NEAs.

NEA Size & Velocity

  • From the definition of PHAs, PHAs should be larger on average than non-hazardous NEAs.

  • Our expectation is correct, hazardous NEAs are larger on average than non-hazardous NEAs. Again, much larger range for non-hazardous asteroids on both ends of the spectrum.
  • The mean, being more subject to outliers, is significantly different than the median for both hazard classifications of asteroid sizes.
  • As expected, hazardous NEAs have a much greater relative velocity on average than non-hazardous NEAs.

433 Eros

433 Eros

  • 433 Eros is the first asteroid to be orbited by a satellite and the first to have a satellite land on its surface (NEAR Shoemaker).
  • This is an actual photo from NASAs CNEOS website taken by NEAR Shoemaker.
  • 433 Eros is of NEA class Amors and ended up being slightly smaller than expected: 34 km x 11.2 km x 11.2 km
  • The asteroid (or comet) that wiped out the dinosaurs is estimated to be 10 km in diameter
  • Thank goodness 433 Eros isnt Hazardous!

Perihelion Distance and Eccentricity

  • A nice visual display of how perihelion distance is used to calculate asteroid class.
  • Also a nice visual of the relationship between eccentricity and perihelion distance.
  • The greater the perihelion distance the lower the eccentricity which is due to eccentricity being used to calculate perihelion distance:
    • P = semi-major axis * (1 - eccentricity).
  • This graph also displays the perihelion cut-off for PHAs (a little above 1 AU).

  • How close do these objects get to the Earth?

  • On average non-hazardous NEAs miss by less than hazardous NEAs.
    • Looks like a small difference but its important to remember that these are measured in astronomical units (1 au is approximately 149,598,000 km).
  • Non-hazardous NEAs are smaller on average so many of them wouldnt be classified as potentially hazardous even though they miss earth by less distance on average.

Summary

  • Problem Statements:
    • What are the differences between Hazardous and Non-Hazardous asteroids?
    • What are the differences between the classifications of NEAs?
  • These questions were answered by comparing the selected variables separated by hazard and NEA classification via graphs and basic statistics.
  • Interesting Insights
    • NEAs are classified by orbit (inside earths orbit, intersecting earths orbit but mostly inside, intersecting earths orbit but mostly outside, and outside earths orbit)
    • Most NEAs are Amors, Apollos, Atens class.
      • Most hazardous asteroids are Apollo or Atens class (over 96%).
      • There are very few Atiras class NEAs.
    • Orbital uncertainty is very low in Hazardous NEAs (mean is 0!)
      • As mentioned earler, this is probably because we spend more time observing PHAs
    • Hazardous asteroids are less visible and larger on average (as expected from how PHAs are defined).
      • The largest NEA in this data set (433 Eros) is non-hazardous.
    • Hazardous asteroids have a significantly greater relative velocity.
  • Implications of our findings
    • We are more aware of the celestial bodies in our neighborhood than ever before.
    • This should allow us to be better prepared to avoid potentially devastating impacts and to keep our astronauts & satellites safe.
    • As our technology advances, humans should have a better idea of which asteroids to mine (once/if that becomes possible).
  • Limitations
    • WWould have liked if there had been an estimated mass variable for these NEOs. This would have opened up more possibilities for more calculations (gravity, momentum, etc.).
    • NASAs CNEOS has found significantly more NEOs since this dataset was compiled (433 Eros is no longer the largest NEA).
    • A big limitation is my lack of knowledge of physics and astronomy, being able to work with an astronomer would have been a big help.
    • More information on asteroid composition would be nice but advances in technology are necessary for this to be available.
